Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 475 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Halve, peel, and finely dice @red onion{1}(finely diced); reserve 2 TBSP in a #small bowl{} for step 5. Core, deseed, and dice @long green pepper{1}(diced into 1/2-inch pieces). Drain and rinse @black beans{1%unit}.

Finely dice @tomato{1}(finely diced). Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}(roughly chopped). Quarter @lime{1}(quartered).

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tbsp} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add garlic and 2 TBSP remaining onion; cook, stirring constantly, until garlic is fragrant and onion is translucent, ~{1-3%minutes}.

Stir in @jasmine rice{3/4%cup} and half the @tomato paste{1.5%oz}; cook, stirring, until rice is evenly coated, ~{30-60%seconds} more.

Stir in 1 1/4 cups @water{1 1/4%cups}, @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tsp}, and @salt{1%tsp}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Pat @chicken breast strips{10%oz} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with @Mexican Spice Blend{1%tbsp}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Heat a large drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat.

Add chicken in a single layer; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and almost cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add green pepper and remaining onion; cook, stirring, until slightly softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add half the beans, half the @Mexican Cheese Blend{1/2%cup}, remaining Southwest Spice Blend, and 1/2 cup @water{1/2%cup}. Cook, stirring, until filling has thickened and chicken is cooked through, ~{2-4%minutes} more. Remove from heat; taste and season with salt and pepper.

Wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp #paper towels{} and microwave until warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}.

Place a small amount of filling on one half of each tortilla. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create enchiladas. Place, seam sides down, in an 8-by-11-inch #baking dish{} or large #ovenproof pan{}.

Pour @enchilada sauce{10%oz} over enchiladas to thoroughly coat. (You might not need all the sauce.) Top with remaining Mexican cheese blend. Bake on top rack until sauce is bubbly and cheese melts, ~{6-8%minutes}.

While enchiladas bake, stir tomato, cilantro, and a squeeze of lime juice to taste into #bowl{} with reserved onion; season with salt and pepper.

In a second small bowl, combine @sour cream{3%tbsp} with a squeeze of lime juice to taste. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with salt and pepper.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @butter{1%tbsp} until melted.

Top enchiladas with lime crema and as much pico de gallo as you like. Divide rice between plates. Serve enchiladas directly from baking dish with remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Spoon some pico on top of your rice for an extra hit of tomato.

> Saucy, smothered, hearty, and delicious—it’s everything husband Neil Patrick Harris' heart (and stomach) desires!